Thank you for your sweet spirit and positive influence in my daughter's life.
She found you after giving birth to her child. She started yoga to get back in shape but soon realized there were many more benefits. It set her on a path of healing and wellness. She received her certifications after attending yoga teacher's training at Indra's Grace yoga studio where she now teaches. It has helped her to heal some traumas she experienced as a young adult. I believe it also put her on a mindful parenting track as well. Watching her transformation inspired me to start my own self-care and healing journey as well. As a mom of 5 kids I was always putting everyone else ahead of my own development, which I was happy to do. However I have come to realize that by prioritizing some time for ourselves, those around us benefit as well. Thank you for causing such a wonderful ripple effect in our lives as well as so many others lives around the world. You are helping to heal our bodies, minds and spirits. Much love and gratitude from North Texas.ðŸ’œðŸ’œðŸ’œ

Day 1 - Here we go, off to Yoga Camp!! I completed the 30 Days Journey (2015) a few weeks ago and now I"m READY and looking forward to start again! Not only have I seen a change in myself, OTHERS - have noticed the change within me as well! "You seem more relaxed and chill!" "Something is different about you, I can't quiet figure it out" - my reply:  "Thank you so much!  I just completed a 30 day "Yoga with Adriene" journey. It's changed the way I think about myself and it's pouring out of my pores!!" <3  Biggest Change:  I've stopped with my nasty negative inner dialogue whenever I saw myself naked in the mirror. I would always focus on the wobbly bits and everything that is not to the "Social Media" standard. But ya know, this wobbly body made it through 30 days of Yoga and I turned out better for it! Don't think if you can do this! I KNOW YOU CAN! You WILL! You GOT THIS!!! - I"m just a day ahead of you!  I'll wait for you at day 30 - we can leave Camp together! WE GOT THIS!!!! Namaste! 

5 years ago my best friend died on Jan 1, 2015. She and I had the same tattoo on lower backs, it symbolized "Girl I Got Your Back". "And still, after all this time,
The sun never says to the earth, "You owe Me".

Look what happens with
A love like that.
It lights the Whole Sky"

- Hafiz

I studied yoga for one term in college, also I took Laban Movement at a university for one term. I have taken several Physical Education courses over 20 credits, all of them one credit a course. I trained to be a Combat Medic in the U.S. Army. I also worked in construction for several years in my younger adult years. I took a little martial arts and aerobic weight training in my early 20's. I had a journey learning to work and living skills. I am catholic and worshipped God as often as I could living as an Adult. I studied Laban Movement for a term and another 3 months private course of Modern Dance when I was 30. I have trained to be a triatholon athlete running and swimming, riding a bike. Because I had such a wide variety of physical training and learned discipline from work, Yoga was a little different to mentally experience. I learned in the army strength training in a different manner, you never relax in the army. You are totally challenged to learn a mental strength for using weapons and being very alert, so that you can respond to attack at a fraction of a second. When I got out of the army I had to re-train to learn to live again among civilian. I wasn't in very long even. However war training is nothing like civilian training and mentally changes your bearing in life. I don't stick with yoga stretches after the class I took but I do combine my laban movement with some martial art like forms and a bit of yoga like stretches.  Last night I came up with some project similar to your yoga camp. I started with the Rising Sun, then the sun's course, Then the Moon, and today I started the Waters of Life, and will keep going through them until I have renewed my mind and body a bit. I took a few years off from fitness to do some online courses at a university. What I don't like about Yoga is the origins of some of the religious aspects of yoga meditations , I learned to meditate in a crisis hotline operator class. As a Catholic I don't think old world religions are the best source for spiritual guidance, but the exercises I think take some of the conventional boredoms out of life and do help your health. I am more into strength and endurance exercise myself, like hiking and running. Well just wanted to share , I think out of sheer boredom ,  I don't know.

I had already done 30daysofyoga with you in 2015, multiple times, and LOVED it. So I started Yoga Camp in Feb 2016, but just before I started, things in my life got extremely out of control and too much to handle, I had just moved country; everything went wrong. I was in an extremely bad place mentally, and after Day 5 I stopped all yoga (and all exercise) for 5 months! Easily the longest I have been without 'movement'. I wasn't eating or sleeping properly, I would barely leave the tiny house. It was horrible. When I returned to my home country in August, I started Yoga (30daysofYWA) with you again. I was so amazed by how hard it was for me, I was so out of practice!! I was so frustrated; it was worse than 'beginner me'. But I trusted you, and the difference you made in my life before, and stuck with it. Completed the 30days on the 1st of Oct. I made the best progress!

Then, I wanted to try do Yoga Camp, but I was so terrified that the memories and flashbacks would be triggered by Yoga Camp considering I was doing it at the time everything happened. It sounds silly, I knew it was silly, but I couldn't help be scared that it would bring up all those feelings again by way of association. After a few days of trepidation and hesitation, I took a deep breath in  and decided to watch the orientation camp video again. I decided to commit to finding what feels good and Yoga Camp, it was a leap of faith. 
Well, I have now completed Day 7 of Yoga Camp!  

I'm sorry my comment is so long, I just knew I had to come back to Day 1 and get this out and encourage anyone else starting this challenge. 
I never comment on anything, until starting Yoga Camp. You asked in the orientation video to connect to the community, I have heard you say it so many times. But now I am :) and I am so grateful to be a part of it!

Recently I sustained a knee injury (embarrassingly enough I was sitting down and twisted it the wrong way) and I haven't been able to practice yoga as much as I had previously. So I decided do do this video as a way to try and come back to my practice. I found myself getting emotional and frustrated when I realized that because of my injury (basically my knee pops out of the socket repeatedly and it's super painful) I could no longer do child's pose, a pose I used to love to relax in. I started thinking about the affirmation and I wasn't sure if I was supposed to accept that this is where my knee is right now or that this is the way I felt about everything. I realized you probably would have told me to accept both so I tried to do just that and took my practice slow and steady. Hopefully I will be able to get to where I was but even if I can't your bright personality helps to curb the negative thoughts that sometimes creep in when people practice yoga. Thank you Adriene for all the time and effort you put into your videos, I want you to know that people are grateful and that it really does make a difference.

Thank you for the time and effort it takes to put these together. I find the criss cross position quite uncomfortable- always have. You always say "sit in a comfortable position" and it just not. By the time we move, my outer ankle and foot are in pain. Is there anything you would suggest?  My outer hips are also tight but I think that will improve in time.

This was such a great place to start. I am setting the intention of commenting on every video, as a way to "check in" and keep myself accountable (and I invite others to join in this practice!)...stay in touch!

One insight that came through this practice was about how, when beginning a new fitness-related activity (which I do NOT do often, as I have some barriers, both physical and psychological, to engaging my body), I often project that I am beginning it as a NEW me; a fantasized version of myself, that will work harder than I want to work, endure more pain that i have before, be skinny, be DIFFERENT. And today, with this simple statement, "I accept," I could step into my experience as it is right now. Not the perfect version of me. Just me. :) Thank you!
